The dialogus, however, is always terse and animated, the narrative at times very pic· turesque, and the situations exhibit much sentimental pathos. Simo’s story in the first scene is praised by Cicero¹ as a descriptiva masterpiece. Other passages of singular vivid- ness are the charge of Chrysis on her death-bed (282-298), and Davus' recital of his observations at Chremes’ house (353 a). For excellent specimens of refined and sprightly dialogus, see Act II, Soeue 63 Act Ill, Scene 3 3 and Act V, Scene 3.

aa The characters in the Andria are distinctly and con· sistently portrayed. The young man Pamphilus has a com- panionable and complaisant disposition, which is well described by Simo in his conversation with Sosia (62-68). Pamphilus, however, is much more sentimental than Simo had supposed. He has a genuine respect for his father, and desires to submit to his will, but his love is strong enough to make him thoroughly true to the object of his affectione. In no other respect, however, is Pamphilus a strong char- acter. He shows indecision (264), is afraid to confess his passion to an indulgent parent, relies upon a slave's judg- ment rather than his own (336), and, in accordante with the knave’s advice, deceives his father by a lie (420).
